howcase new theoretical frameworks and approaches from law, history, medicine, women’s studies, and political science as they document the diversity of abortion experiences across the country, from those of Indigenous women in the pre-Morgentaler era to a lack of access in the age of so-called decriminalization. Together, the contributors make a case for shifting the debate from abortion rights to reproductive justice and caution against focusing on “choice” or medicalization without understanding the broader context of why and when people seek out abortions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbortionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aAckerman, Katrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeausaert, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Lori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnett, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnett, Kristin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChapman, Frances E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoull, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyck, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrlich, J. Shoshanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHay, Travis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHay, Travis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnstone, Rachael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLight, Tracy Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r